{"tid":1011220,"cid":5,"subCid":0,"title":"瑞士國會：華為可能威脅國家安全","createTime":"2019-02-06T15:03:50.000Z","updateTime":"2019-02-07T01:50:13.000Z","uid":47714,"like":34,"dislike":2,"uniUserReply":17,"replies":[{"pid":"ab8fcfec14ad107f079320312d1d608bdde9278c","tid":1011220,"uid":47714,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2019-02-06T15:03:50.000Z","msg":"<a href=\"https://www.telecompaper.com/news/swiss-parliament-deals-with-national-security-concerns-over-huawei--1278306\" data-sr-url=\"https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.telecompaper.com%2Fnews%2Fswiss-parliament-deals-with-national-security-concerns-over-huawei--1278306&d=8mXO1VLy4U8nFH7Q%2FrHVYEoInKkgZqzseva8eQDkMF8%3D&h=fb8f5c80\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.telecompaper.com/news/swiss-parliament-deals-with-national-security-concerns-over-huawei--1278306</a><br />\n<br />\nWednesday 30 January 2019<br />\n<br />\nThe Swiss Parliament has started looking into the possibility that Huawei could represent a threat to national security. The Parliamentary Security Commission has begun examining the Chinese technology supplier with a magnifying glass, reports RTS.ch. The investigation should provide the basis for decision-making. <br />\n<br />\nHuawei has been under pressure for some time. Governments in the US, Australia and Japan have banned Huawei from their 5G markets. The US called on its allies to boycott Huawei, as the Wall Street Journal reported.<br />\n<br />\nIn Switzerland, however, there has been restraint from criticism, with Sunrise and Swisscom both backing Huawei. When asked, a Sunrise spokesman said it is &quot;fully satisfied&quot; with the quality of its technology partner Huawei and has no plans to change supplier. Of the Swiss operators, Sunrise is the most intertwined with Huawei, the NZZ reports. Sunrise and Huawei jointly put the first 5G antenna into operation at the end of June 2018."},{"pid":"f5b7c803129a6f7124a39bd27a7e7cb4f2c8fe0c","tid":1011220,"uid":41389,"like":0